## THE EMPTY NEST — AND CHRISTMAS

By the time her youngest two are grown, Patti Anne's four children are scattered across the planet, and she is at peace with it:

- **Gamaliel & Klára** — Prague (their ballet academy).
- **Palmer Peter** — Saudi Arabia (Muslim convert; his own household).
- **Salena Sarai** — Perth, Australia (WAAPA; the farthest of all).

### She wants to be alone — but never at Christmas

Patti Anne, contrary to the worried-mother stereotype, **genuinely wants her solitude.** The eldest of eight, the family anchor, the woman who carried everyone's weight her whole life — she finds the empty nest is not a wound but a **rest.** She and Aleksander like the quiet house. She does not need her grown children orbiting her to feel whole; she raised them so well precisely *because* she always meant for them to go.

**The one exception is Christmas.** Patti Anne can do her own solitude all year — but **not over Christmas.** Christmas is the Key family's holy season (the big gatherings at Mike and Terri Anne's; the Christmas Willow came in a box; the too-Catholic, too-loud, too-much family she would not trade). At Christmas, the woman who is happy alone all year needs her people. This is her one stated terms with the empty nest: *leave me to my quiet — except then.*

### How the scattered family solves Christmas (CANON)

The children split the distance so that **no one is alone at Christmas** and Patti Anne is never alone *over Christmas*. The defining instance is **the first Christmas after the twins leave** — when **Palmer Peter and Salena Sarai are eighteen, Gamaliel is thirty-one,** and Gamaliel & Klára's daughters **Klárka Pavlínka is six and Simonka Káta is five.**

- **Palmer Peter visits Patti Anne and Aleksander.** Her son comes *home* — back to Canada, to the family house — for the season. **At this first Christmas he has not yet converted to Islam** (he is eighteen; the conversion comes at twenty, two years into his Saudi life). So this homecoming is a still-Catholic son simply coming home for Christmas — the conversion is not yet part of the picture.
- **Gamaliel & Klára's family meets Salena Sarai in the middle of her country tour.** Salena Sarai is in the midst of her **two-month Sydney-to-Perth tour** (the Australian summer, before her late-Jan/Feb start at WAAPA). Rather than wait for her to settle in Perth, **the Prague family — Gamaliel (31), Klára, and their two little girls, Klárka (6) and Simonka (5) — flies to Australia and joins Salena on the road, mid-tour,** for Christmas. They meet her somewhere in the middle of the route (around the red centre / south coast leg), so the farthest-flung Key has family with her at Christmas even while she is still roaming. **The visit then runs through New Year's Eve:** the group travels to **Sydney** (where Salena's tour began) for the **harbour fireworks** — the deliberate inversion of the Keys' snow-and-stars cottage New Year where Klára once named Willow — before the family scatters: **Klára flies on to Rio de Janeiro to recruit teachers for the academy, Gamaliel takes the two girls home to Prague,** and Salena continues west to Perth. *(Season clash worth using: an Australian-summer Christmas — heat, no snow — and two small Prague-raised girls, 6 and 5, experiencing it; the opposite of every snowy Key Christmas before it.)*

The result is a deliberately balanced map: **Palmer Peter → home to Mom; the Prague family → out to Salena Sarai on her tour.** Both ends of the earth covered, Patti Anne held at Christmas, and the most isolated child not left alone on the one day it would hurt most.

> **Later Christmases (after Palmer Peter converts at twenty).** Once Palmer Peter is Muslim, his continued homecomings gain a quiet grace: a Muslim son coming back to Canada at Christmas not for the Mass but **for his mother** — welcomed exactly the same, because Patti Anne loves him no matter what (see `Palmer Peter/palmer-peter-key-profile.md`). The family doctrine — *door cracked, porch light on* — paying off across a faith divide. *(Whether the Palmer-home / Prague-to-Salena split becomes the fixed annual pattern, or rotates, is TBD.)*

> **Why this fits Patti Anne:** her version of motherhood at this stage is not clinging; it is *engineering the world so her children are loved and not alone,* then enjoying her quiet the rest of the year. The anchor, still anchoring — just from a comfortable chair in a quiet house, eleven months out of twelve.

**Timeline anchor (derived):** because the twins are 18 / Gamaliel is 31 while Klárka is 6 and Simonka is 5, **Gamaliel was about 25 when Klárka was born** (≈26 for Simonka, fifteen months later). This is now the saga's fixed link between the two generations' clocks.

